# Programming Standards — `actions`

For any programming task in this repo, follow the `senior-coding-actions` skill at [.cursor/skills/senior-coding-actions/SKILL.md](mdc:.cursor/skills/senior-coding-actions/SKILL.md). Read that skill before making code changes and apply every section.

## Non-negotiable priorities

When something has to give, apply these in order:

1. RPC minimization via multicall — new reads in the same flow MUST join an existing multicall batch; standalone calls only for genuinely independent reads.
2. ABI JSON-first — never author or extend ABIs in TypeScript. If a method / event / full ABI is missing from JSON, STOP and ask the user whether the agent should generate the JSON automatically or whether the user will drop it in themselves.
3. Transaction preflight — every on-chain write runs `estimateGas` first. On revert: decode the custom error / revert reason and show it to the user before the wallet prompt. On success: reuse the estimated gas for the actual send. Applies to single calls and multicall batches.
4. Brand-consistent UI — reuse existing components, tokens, spacing, and colors; do not introduce one-off visual styles.
5. Quality gates — `npm run lint`, `npm run type-check`, and `npm run build` must be clean before the task is done.
6. Versioning + CHANGELOG — branch-aware:
   - `release/*` or `hotfix/*` branch: bump `version` in `package.json` (release → minor/major, hotfix → patch; if the branch name encodes the version, use it) AND add a new `## [x.y.z] - YYYY-MM-DD` section with today's date, one-line entry under `Added` / `Updated` / `Fixed`.
   - any other branch: do NOT change `package.json` version; add a one-line entry only under `## [Unreleased]` in the correct category.

## Operational rules

- Before running any Node / npm / build / lint / test command, use the Node version from `.nvmrc` (`nvm use`).
- New dependencies: strict exact versions (no `^`, no `~`) and a quick security check on X/Twitter for recent alerts before choosing the version.
- Leave a short architectural comment only when the code relies on legacy, carries a non-obvious constraint, or is a workaround — focus on the "why" and future risk. No narrating comments.

Task is done only when all of the above are satisfied. Do not hand off with failing lint, type-check, or build, and do not skip the CHANGELOG entry.
